<subSubSection id="FDAA651F063D2E71FF48FBD5FBAF22CA" pageId="23" pageNumber="324" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B50F3694063D2E71FF48FBD5FBAF22CA" blockId="23.[151,1437,1497,1957]" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">
<emphasis id="87C4EA86063D2E71FF48FBD5FED1225E" bold="true" box="[199,315,1786,1812]" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">Remarks.</emphasis>
A notable feature of 
<taxonomicName id="72B04D17063D2E71FDA2FBD5FCCD225E" baseAuthorityName="Ihle" baseAuthorityYear="1913" box="[557,807,1786,1812]" class="Malacostraca" family="Dromiidae" genus="Epigodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="23" pageNumber="324" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="areolata">
<emphasis id="87C4EA86063D2E71FDA2FBD5FCCD225E" box="[557,807,1786,1812]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">Epigodromia areolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the sexual dimorphism. Males have much more pronounced ornamentation of the carapace and chelipeds than in females, and the chelipeds are much larger (
<figureCitation id="2D8B2A11063D2E71FAB5FA31FA7D2273" box="[1338,1431,1822,1849]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[457,1131,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-19@25.[457,1131,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 15. Epigodromia areolata (Ihle, 1913), ovigerous female, 10.6 × 10.7 mm (WAM-C50514):A, dorsal view; B, frontal view; C, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501057" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501057/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">Figs. 15</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="2D8B2A11063D2E71FF18FA6DFF5C2217" box="[151,182,1858,1885]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[357,1229,181,1844]" captionTargetId="figure-21@26.[357,1229,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 16. Epigodromia areolata (Ihle, 1913), male, 16.0 × 14.0 mm (WAM-C50514): A, dorsal view; B, frontal view; C, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501061/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">16</figureCitation>
). The present specimens represent new records for 
<collectingRegion id="7774F876063D2E71FC8EFA6DFC202216" box="[769,970,1858,1884]" country="Australia" name="Western Australia" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">Western Australia</collectingRegion>
and the Indian Ocean coast of 
<collectingCountry id="CDA77604063D2E71FAA0FA6DFA732216" box="[1327,1433,1858,1884]" name="Australia" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">Australia</collectingCountry>
, having been previously reported from Cape Moreton, 
<collectingRegion id="7774F876063D2E71FD7BFA49FC9222CA" box="[756,888,1894,1920]" country="Australia" name="Queensland" pageId="23" pageNumber="324">Queensland</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation id="D1214B65063D2E71FC08FA49FBD322CA" author="Campbell, B. M." box="[903,1081,1894,1920]" pageId="23" pageNumber="324" pagination="27 - 48" refId="ref25106" refString="Campbell, B. M. (1971) New records and new species of crabs (Crustacea: Brachyura) trawled off Southern Queensland: Dromiacea, Homolidae, Gymnopleura, Corystoidea and Oxystomata. Memoirs Queensland Museum, 16, 27 - 48." type="journal article" year="1971">Campbell 1971</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
